# even in 2026, learning c is still high-leverage — not because it's modern,
# but because so much of computing is built on it and inherits its shape.


# 1. it's the ground floor

# the linux kernel, bsds, the macos xnu kernel, the windows nt kernel, every
# major libc, cpython, the ruby / php / lua interpreters, sqlite, postgresql,
# redis, ffmpeg, openssl, git, curl, nginx, postfix — all c. even rust and go
# compilers ship runtimes that interoperate with c abis. learning c is learning
# the substrate.


# 2. the c abi is the universal interface

# every language eventually grows an ffi to c — because that's how libraries
# cross language boundaries:
# - python ctypes
# - node n-api
# - ruby ffi
# - go cgo
# - rust extern "C"
# - swift @_cdecl
# all of them target the c calling convention. if you ever want to bridge two
# languages, you go through c.


# 3. it teaches you how computers actually work

# manual memory, pointers, stack vs heap, struct layout, integer promotion,
# undefined behavior, what "the compiler" even does. higher-level languages
# hide these — but they don't go away; they just hide *where the surprises
# come from*. most "weird" python or js performance behavior makes sense once
# you've written c.


# 4. embedded / kernel / driver work is still c-dominated

# microcontrollers, real-time oses, anything with strict size constraints,
# anything talking directly to silicon. rust is making inroads but c is still
# the lingua franca.


# 5. reading source code

# a huge fraction of "how does this actually work" answers — for any tool you
# use daily — live in c source trees. being able to read them is a superpower.


# honest counterpoints

# - for *new* systems software in 2026, rust is the safer default. memory
#   safety wins; the borrow checker is worth the friction.
# - for *application* work, c is the wrong tool. use go, rust, python, ts —
#   whatever fits the domain.
# - c will not get you a job by itself. it's an underlay, not a career.


# the take

# learn c to ~k&r fluency (you don't need to be a wizard) precisely because
# it's 50 years old. the half-life of that knowledge is enormous — it'll still
# be relevant in 2046. compare that to whatever js framework is currently hot.
# c is one of the highest-roi things a working programmer can invest a month in.
#
# then learn rust right after — they pair beautifully. c teaches you what the
# problems are; rust teaches you the modern answer.
